      <h1 class="article__title">
        The 90/180 Rolling Window for the Schengen Area, Explained Visually
      </h1>

      <p class="article__meta">June 8, 2026 · 10 min read</p>

      <p class="article__audience">
        <strong>This post is for you if:</strong> you're planning a long-term
        trip with more than one stay in the Schengen Area, and you want to
        keep your plans flexible without accidentally overstaying.
        <br/>
        <br/>
        <strong>It's probably not necessary if:</strong> you're taking a
        single trip under 90 days with no return visits planned. In that
        case, the rule is simple and a single calculation will tell you
        everything you need to know.
      </p>
    </header>



    <div class="article__body">

    <p>
        When planning an extended trip in Europe, you'll quickly encounter the
        following advice: spend 90 days in the{" "}
        <a
          href="https://home-affairs.ec.europa.eu/policies/schengen-borders-and-visa/schengen-area_en"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          >Schengen Area</a
        >, leave for 90 days <em>and then</em> you can come back. It sounds clean and
        while it's technically correct, it's a rigid misrepresentation of the rule.
    </p>
    <p>
        If you want to plan a long-term European itinerary with confidence, it's critical to understand how the 90/180 rule actually works.
        This is the key to keeping a year-long trip flexible and visa-free.
    </p>

